<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,1362,1599]" box="[151,974,1362,1387]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,458,1362,1387]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis and description</emphasis>
. As given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Masan" box="[615,777,1362,1387]" firstAuthor="Masan" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="ref43485" refString="Masan, P. (2007 a) A Review of the Family Pachylaelapidae in Slovakia, with Systematics and Ecology of European Species (Acari: Mesostigmata: Eviphidoidea). Institute of Zoology, Slovak Academy of Sciences, Bratislava, 247 pp." type="book" year="2007" yearSuffix="a">Mašán (2007a</bibRefCitation>
, pages 192–194).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,1362,1599]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Masan" authorityYear="2014" box="[151,366,1396,1421]" class="Arachnida" family="Pachylaelapidae" genus="Pachyglobolaelaps" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,366,1396,1421]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Pachyglobolaelaps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a highly specialised monotypic genus described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Masan" box="[979,1151,1396,1421]" firstAuthor="Masan" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="ref43485" refString="Masan, P. (2007 a) A Review of the Family Pachylaelapidae in Slovakia, with Systematics and Ecology of European Species (Acari: Mesostigmata: Eviphidoidea). Institute of Zoology, Slovak Academy of Sciences, Bratislava, 247 pp." type="book" year="2007" yearSuffix="a">Mašán (2007a)</bibRefCitation>
. Perhaps as a result of its myrmecophilous mode of life, it differs from all the other pachylaelapid genera in having an extended and highly vaulted dorsal shield overlapping the lateral sides of the idiosoma and encroaching onto the ventral surface, a tubular sperm access system, minute microsetae J5, and an unusual arrangement of dorsal setae, some of which are in ventral positions. The highly distorted and arched dorsal shield makes it extremely difficult to homologise these setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
